# Performance & Code Fragility

## Avoid Per-Frame Allocations

- **Reuse lists**: Use instance fields (e.g. `_buffer = new List<T>(capacity)`), `Clear()` and reuse. Never `new List<T>()` in `Update`, `FixedUpdate`, or per-frame logic.
- **GetComponentsInChildren**: Use the `List<T>` overload: `GetComponentsInChildren(false, _resultsBuffer)` instead of the allocating array return.
- **Color/Vector3**: Prefer cached structs; avoid `new Color(...)` in per-frame code if profiling shows GC pressure.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: allocates every frame
void Update() {
    var list = new List<Transform>();
    GetTransformsAtBlock(x, y, z, list);
}

// ✅ GOOD: reuse buffer
private readonly List<Transform> _buffer = new List<Transform>(8);
void Update() {
    _buffer.Clear();
    GetTransformsAtBlock(x, y, z, _buffer);
}
```

## Material & Shader Lifecycle

- **Destroy materials** you instantiate: `Object.Destroy(material)` in `OnDestroy` or when discarding (e.g. preview `Release()`).
- **Cache Shader.Find**: Never call `Shader.Find` in hot paths. Cache in instance/static field on first use. Use `ShaderNames` constants.
- **Shared vs instantiated**: Prefer one shared material for similar visuals; destroy only when the owning object is disposed.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Shader.Find per quad; material leak
var mat = new Material(Shader.Find("Sprites/Default"));

// ✅ GOOD: cache shader; destroy material in Release/OnDestroy
_defaultShader ??= Shader.Find(ShaderNames.Fallback);
_roadOverlayMaterial ??= new Material(_defaultShader) { color = RemovalColor };
// ... in Release(): if (_roadOverlayMaterial != null) Object.Destroy(_roadOverlayMaterial);
```

## Object.Destroy vs DestroyImmediate

- Use `Object.Destroy` at runtime. Never `DestroyImmediate` outside Editor scripts.

## Avoid Hardcoded Values

- **Entry names**: Use `PlacedObjectKeys` (Road, Tree, Actors, Warehouse) or registry-driven lookup (e.g. `GetGlobalStorageEntry()`).
- **Shader names**: Use `ShaderNames` constants.
- **Magic numbers**: Extract to named constants (`const int BufferCapacity = 32`, `const float Epsilon = 0.001f`).

## Extensibility

- **Avoid name checks**: Use registry flags (e.g. `entry.UsesGlobalStorage`) instead of `name == "Warehouse"`.
- **Avoid enum switches for types**: Prefer `ActorDefinition.BehaviorTypeName` or registry mapping so new kinds don't require code changes.
- **Data-driven over code**: Add new structures/items via ScriptableObjects and registry entries, not enum edits and switch cases.
